        %ul
          %li
            %strong Carat weight is less a “grade” than it is a measurement.
            %blockquote
              It is important to note that Carat is a measure of weight, not size. In most cases, diamonds get larger as they get heavier, but this is not always the case. Cut affects the appearance of the size as well.
            %p
              What is really means is that carat weight is determined by placing the diamond on a very accurate scale, and is not subject to interpretation.
            .panel.callout.radius
              We have such a scale in our office, and it is so sensitive that we have to turn off the air (and any fans) to ensure we get a stable and accurate reading.

          %li
            %strong The size of a diamond is primarily related to it's millimeter measurements
            %blockquote
              While not a proper C, measurements and carat weight are related. So we'll talk about it here
            %p
              Every certificate has a diamond's size measurements in addition to it's carat weight, and they are worth checking out. They look something like this:
              %pre.text-center 1.23x4.56x7.89
            %p
              The first number is the diameter of the stone, and may also be referred to as the spread. On a round diamond, this is the length across the top. Other diamonds can have both a length and width, which will be represented by the first 2 numbers. The last number is the height of the stone.
            .panel.callout.radius
              Round diamonds technically have a length and width as well, but they are usually the same, or very close. If they weren't, it would actually be an Oval diamond.

          %li
            %strong Carat weight has a <em>major</em> effect on price
            %blockquote
              A diamond that is twice the weight can cost exponentially more than a smaller diamond.
            %p
              This increase gets larger and larger as diamonds get bigger, but the main takeaway is that you can’t spend twice as much to get a diamond that weighs twice as much.

          %li
            %strong <em>"Under Size"</em> diamonds can save you money
            %blockquote
              Under sizes are diamonds that are very close to a cut off size. The cut offs are mainly at each half carat, so 1.00ct-1.50ct-2.00ct and so on. An example of an under size would be 0.90ct or a 1.47ct.
            %p
              They are important because an under size will be priced based on a completely different and often much lower per carat price. These small weight differences can be very minute, but the difference in price can be much more noticeable.

          %li
            %strong Although it is a cold calculating number, carat weight can be very visual
            %blockquote
              You might be surprised at how small the difference in <em>size</em> is compared to a difference in <em>weight</em> (and cost!).
            %p
              This is why it's a great idea to see some live diamonds to make your decision. Some want to make sure they get at least a certain size, but you should have a look to make sure the difference in size is worth the difference in cost.

