        %p
          Even when diamonds are many grades apart, it can be difficult to notice color differences unless two diamonds are side by side. This is especially true when they are in the same category of diamond colors as shown in the chart.

        %p
          If you're looking to save money, it is often a great idea to get a lower color diamond. As long as your side diamonds are matched to the color of your center stone, your ring will look beautiful. This is one reason why premade rings can cause issues. Since they are already set with diamonds, you won't have the luxury of ensuring they match your center stone.

        .panel.callout.radius
          We generally don't recommend going lower than J color. Past that, the yellow color of a diamond becomes too noticeable.

        %p
          The majority of lower color diamonds exhibit a light yellowish color, but brownish is also possible. As long as you stick with a diamond color of J or higher, you won't have to worry about this.

        %p
          As always, it's always best to have a look at some diamonds in person to come to your own conclusions about color. The big point that I think is important is to not get hung up on numbers and letters on a certificate and let your eyes and heart lead your decision-making.

